# read

Renders a `# read` structural directive as an XML reference block. This is a run-time instruction — the compiler emits the file path and description so the LLM opens and reads the file itself before generating code. Nothing is embedded; the file's contents never appear in the prompt.

`# read` uses a special header syntax: `# read {glob} as [name]`. The compiler extracts the file path from the `{glob}` portion before the `as` keyword and the reference name from the `[name]` portion after it. The description the developer wrote beneath the directive becomes the block body.

# entity Input

- directive: 'read'
- name: the reference identifier from the `as [name]` portion of the header (e.g. 'AppLogger')
- glob: the file path or glob pattern extracted from the `{glob}` portion of the header (e.g. 'src/infrastructure/logger.ts') — provided by the compiler as a parsed header field
- body: the description lines the developer wrote beneath the directive

# entity Output

```markdown
<repository_file name="{{name}}" path="{{glob}}">

{{body}}

Before writing any code that touches this reference, open and read the file(s) at the path above and analyze them carefully. Mirror their existing formatting, export patterns, and error-handling architecture. Do not guess at their contents, and do not reimplement what they already provide.

</repository_file>
```

# rule

- name is required. A read block without a name is a PARSE_ERROR.
- glob is extracted from the `{glob}` portion of the header line (before the `as` keyword), not from the body. It is passed to the template as a parsed field alongside name and body.
- When the glob matches multiple files, the path attribute lists the pattern and the instruction already refers to "the file(s)" — no template change needed.
- The closing `</repository_file>` tag must be on its own line with a blank line before it.
- A missing body (no description) is a compiler warning — the LLM needs the developer's explanation to understand the file's architectural role.
- Read blocks are rendered before all other directive sections so the model receives all file context before reading implementation contracts. The compiler places them immediately after the prompt header.
- If the agent has no filesystem access (e.g. a raw paste into a browser chat), it should ask for the named file(s) rather than inventing their contents — the instruction text already covers this implicitly through "do not guess."
